docs.abstract: The House Ways and Means Committee chairman, using an obscure provision in the tax code, formally demanded President Trump’s personal and business tax returns, most likely starting a momentous fight.
docs.snippet: The House Ways and Means Committee chairman, using an obscure provision in the tax code, formally demanded President Trump’s personal and business tax returns, most likely starting a momentous fight.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee, using a little-known provision in the federal tax code, formally requested on Wednesday that the I.R.S. hand over six years of President Trump’s personal and business tax returns, starting what is likely to be a momentous fight with his administration.

headline.main: House Democrat Demands Six Years of Trump Tax Returns From I.R.S.
headline.print_headline: Lawmaker Seeks 6 Years Of Trump’s Tax Returns

docs.abstract: Liberal Democrats are infuriated by a new Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee policy intended to protect centrist incumbents from primary challenges.
docs.snippet: Liberal Democrats are infuriated by a new Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee policy intended to protect centrist incumbents from primary challenges.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The House Democratic campaign arm is nearing open warfare with the party’s rising liberal wing as political operatives close to Speaker Nancy Pelosi try to shut down primary challenges before what is likely to be a hard-fought campaign next year to preserve the party’s shaky majority.

headline.main: House Democratic Campaign Arm Nears War With Liberals Over Primary Fights
headline.print_headline: House Campaign Arm and Liberal Wing at Odds Over Shielding Centrists

docs.abstract: A key part of the sweeping criminal justice overhaul passed in December was supposed to be in place within 30 days.
docs.snippet: A key part of the sweeping criminal justice overhaul passed in December was supposed to be in place within 30 days.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Justice Department has begun putting a key aspect of last year’s sweeping bipartisan criminal justice overhaul into effect, after delays prompted in part by the partial government shutdown and turnover at the top of the department.

headline.main: Justice Dept. Works on Applying Sentencing Law as Critics Point to Delays
headline.print_headline: Justice Overhaul, Delayed by Shutdown  And Department Tumult, Takes a Step

docs.abstract: Even as he maintained that the policy is effective, President Trump inaccurately said his administration’s practice of separating families on the border should be pinned on his predecessor.
docs.snippet: Even as he maintained that the policy is effective, President Trump inaccurately said his administration’s practice of separating families on the border should be pinned on his predecessor.
docs.lead_paragraph: Mr. Trump has escalated a misleading defense of his administration’s practice of breaking up families to outright revisionist history. There is no law that mandates family separation, let alone a law enacted under Mr. Obama. The practice is the result of a policy enacted by the Trump administration, and ended by Mr. Trump last June.

headline.main: Fact-Checking Trump’s Family Separation Claim about Obama’s Policy

docs.abstract: Samuel Patten had pleaded guilty in a case that grew out of the Mueller investigation. He helped a Ukrainian billionaire illegally buy tickets to President Trump’s inauguration.
docs.snippet: Samuel Patten had pleaded guilty in a case that grew out of the Mueller investigation. He helped a Ukrainian billionaire illegally buy tickets to President Trump’s inauguration.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — An American lobbyist was sentenced Friday to three years of probation and a $5,000 fine for failing to register as a foreign agent for a Russia-friendly political party in Ukraine and for helping a Ukrainian billionaire illegally purchase tickets to President Trump’s inauguration.

headline.main: Lobbyist Gets Probation for Failing to Disclose Work for Pro-Russia Forces in Ukraine

docs.abstract: Bill Morneau, Canada’s finance minister, pressed President Trump’s top economic advisers this week to lift the tariffs on steel and aluminum.
docs.snippet: Bill Morneau, Canada’s finance minister, pressed President Trump’s top economic advisers this week to lift the tariffs on steel and aluminum.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Canada’s top economic diplomat personally lobbied President Trump’s advisers this week to remove American tariffs on Canadian steel and aluminum imports and warned that the levies could jeopardize that country’s ratification of the rewritten North American Free Trade Agreement.

headline.main: U.S. Metal Tariffs Could Jeopardize Trade Deal, Canadian Official Warns
headline.print_headline: U.S. Metal Tariffs Could Jeopardize Trade Deal, Canadian Official Warns

docs.abstract: The Internal Revenue Service is facing an April 23 deadline to comply with a Congressional request.
docs.snippet: The Internal Revenue Service is facing an April 23 deadline to comply with a Congressional request.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump’s personal lawyer on Monday urged the Treasury Department not to hand over Mr. Trump’s tax returns to House Democrats, warning that releasing the documents to lawmakers he accused of having a “radical view of unchecked congressional power” would turn the Internal Revenue Service into a political weapon.

headline.main: Trump Lawyer Urges Treasury Not to Release His Tax Returns
